<section id="overview">
  <h2>Annual Feng Shui: Why It Changes Every Year</h2>
  <p><a href="/fengshui/">Feng shui</a> (<span class="chinese-char">風水</span>) is not a one-time arrangement but a dynamic system that responds to shifting cosmic energies. While the permanent feng shui of a building is determined by its facing direction and construction date, the <strong>annual feng shui</strong> layer changes every Chinese New Year as the <strong>Flying Stars</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">飛星</span>, Fēixīng) rotate into new positions on the nine-sector Luoshu grid.</p>

  <p>The Flying Stars system — formally known as <strong>Xuan Kong Fei Xing</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">玄空飛星</span>, Mysterious Void Flying Stars) — assigns nine stars numbered 1 through 9 to the nine sectors of the Luoshu magic square. Each star carries specific elemental energy and life associations. Every year, the stars rotate one position according to a fixed pattern, placing different energies in different sectors of your home. The <em>Qingnang Aomi</em> (<span class="chinese-char">青囊奧語</span>, Secret Words of the Azure Satchel), attributed to Yang Yunsong of the Tang dynasty, provides the theoretical underpinning for this annual rotation.</p>

  <p>In 2026, the Year of the Fire Horse (<a href="/article-2026-horse/">Bingwu</a>), the annual chart is defined by <strong>Star 2 occupying the Center</strong>. This placement determines where every other star lands and shapes the feng shui landscape for the entire year. Additionally, the year's dominant Fire energy interacts with each star's inherent element, creating sector-specific dynamics that require careful analysis.</p>
</section>

